{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\n\nrebar's three LLM review gates — plan-review, code-review, and completion-verification — each\nproduce a rich internal record, but only a fraction is durably captured today:\n\n- Plan-review and code-review run a shared four-pass kernel (find → verify → decide → coach) and\n  emit a reducer-ignored `REVIEW_RESULT` sidecar. The plan-review sidecar drops the pass-1\n  `evidence` and `scenarios` fields; the code-review sidecar persists only the *surfaced* findings\n  (blocking + advisory + coaching) and omits the dropped / indeterminate / overflow buckets. Neither\n  persists the numeric `block_threshold` a finding was judged against — it is resolved from the\n  criteria registry at decision time and then discarded.\n- Completion-verification is single-pass and emits a sidecar ONLY on FAIL; a PASS persists just\n  signed counts, so a successful close leaves no per-criterion audit record.\n- All review sidecars are pruned to the most recent 10 per ticket.\n\nA downstream feature (the ticket audit-trail UI, a separate follow-on epic) needs a COMPLETE,\nself-contained audit record. This epic makes the stored audit data lossless and readable; it builds\nNO UI. The read layer it ships also makes the audit data scriptable via CLI/MCP — valuable on its own.\n\n## Approach rationale\n\nEnrich the existing observability sidecars in place (new schema versions) rather than introduce a\nnew persistence mechanism — the sidecar path is already the durable, reducer-ignored, retained\nrecord every review writes, so extending its payload is the lowest-blast-radius way to capture the\nmissing data. The signed attestation manifest is deliberately left carrying counts only (its\nintegrity contract is out of scope); this epic enriches observability, not the signature.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- Every new plan-review and code-review `REVIEW_RESULT` sidecar captures the full four-pass record:\n  the complete pass-1 finding list (including previously-dropped fields), the full pass-2\n  verification, the pass-3 determination WITH the resolved numeric threshold, and pass-4 coaching —\n  across ALL buckets, not just surfaced ones.\n- A completion-verification PASS persists a per-criterion audit record (not only counts).\n- Review-sidecar retention is raised so a ticket's review history is deep enough to audit.\n- A documented read API (library + CLI + MCP) returns the full retained audit history for a ticket\n  and resolves a ticket's associated code reviews via the existing `relates_to` links.\n\n## Scope\n\n- IN: sidecar payload enrichment (plan + code), completion PASS-path capture + agent\n  output-contract change, retention-cap change, the audit read layer.\n- OUT: any web UI or rendering (the follow-on epic); asymmetric-key signing; changing what is\n  SIGNED (attestations still carry counts only).\n\n## Compatibility & rollback\n\nSidecar schemas are bumped (`plan_review_result_v2` / `code_review_result_v2` / a completion `_v2`);\nreaders accept BOTH the old `v1` (rendered with the new fields absent) and the new `v2` records, so\npre-existing reviews stay readable and no backfill is required. Each change is inert until it next\nruns; reverting a story restores the prior payload shape with no migration.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] All child stories are closed.\n- [ ] After this epic, a freshly-run plan-review and code-review each write a `*_v2` sidecar whose\n      payload contains every pass-1 finding across all buckets with its pass-2 verification, its\n      pass-3 validity/impact/priority/decision/reason, the resolved numeric `block_threshold`, and\n      the pass-4 coaching. Oracle: an integration test runs a review and asserts on the emitted event\n      JSON.\n- [ ] A completion-verification PASS emits a per-criterion audit record. Oracle: a test asserting on\n      the emitted completion event.\n- [ ] The audit read layer returns the full retained history for a ticket and its `relates_to`-linked\n      code reviews. Oracle: an integration test seeding a ticket's histories and asserting the\n      aggregate contains all of them."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784082753083557001,"uuid":"8020bdca-ef1f-48e1-87e8-a3886319d2b2"}